The human form of mad cow disease is called variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob.
The fatal brain-wasting disease is believed to come from eating beef products from cows struck with mad cow disease.
Ireland banned the use of meat and bone meal as cattle feed, the suspected origin of mad cow disease, in 1990.
Canada has been testing cattle for BSE since 1992, but boosted testing levels after a single case of mad cow disease was found in Alberta in May 2003.
No cases of mad cow disease have been registered in Bulgaria, where beef meat began to be closely examined for the disease in 2001.
